        <abstract>
            <p>Discusses dimorphic and trimorphic plants; mentions especially Rubiaceae and a dimorphic monocotyledon.</p> 
<p>Notes observations on the monstrous male flowers of <hi rend="italic">Begonia</hi>,</p> 
            <p>and on self-sterile plants.</p>
